00:20:13,167 --> 00:20:15,033
- My friend saw a man
sitting on a cliff.

266
00:20:15,900 --> 00:20:17,600
But I saw something
so much more.

267
00:20:19,100 --> 00:20:20,533
His tortured soul.

268
00:20:21,933 --> 00:20:23,533
- Why do you think he
sits there like that,

269
00:20:23,533 --> 00:20:24,700
with his head buried?

270
00:20:29,700 --> 00:20:31,033
- I, you know...

271
00:20:31,933 --> 00:20:34,200
I always felt he was
suffocated, stuck in a way.

272
00:20:34,867 --> 00:20:36,433
Like he wanted to look forward,

273
00:20:36,433 --> 00:20:38,033
wanted to see the
future, but he couldn't.

274
00:20:38,033 --> 00:20:39,333
He couldn't know
what was coming.

275
00:20:41,467 --> 00:20:43,367
- Why do you feel
suffocated, Dr. Pyatt?

276
00:20:46,600 --> 00:20:47,600
- Isn't this your session?

277
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:48,800
- Forgive me.

278
00:20:49,133 --> 00:20:50,933
- No, no, no, no, don't
worry, don't worry.

279
00:20:51,867 --> 00:20:53,067
Maybe you're right.

280
00:20:59,600 --> 00:21:00,867
- What if the boy
by the sea is not

281
00:21:00,867 --> 00:21:02,233
angry at the at the road ahead?

282
00:21:02,867 --> 00:21:04,300
What if it's the road that came?

283
00:21:06,900 --> 00:21:08,333
- I'm not sure I follow.

284
00:21:09,867 --> 00:21:12,500
- What if he's haunted by
things he cannot change?

285
00:21:14,567 --> 00:21:16,100
- Does something haunt you?

286
00:21:16,100 --> 00:21:17,767
- Something haunts all of us.

287
00:21:20,100 --> 00:21:21,967
- Let's go back to what
you were saying earlier.

288
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:24,867
You said there was
something missing,

289
00:21:24,867 --> 00:21:26,900
something you couldn't
see but wanted to see.

290
00:21:26,900 --> 00:21:28,367
Let's go back to that.

291
00:21:29,733 --> 00:21:32,467
- I don't think it's something
many people could accept.

292
00:21:32,467 --> 00:21:34,867
- Well, it's my
job to understand.

293
00:21:36,333 --> 00:21:37,867
- Yes, I know it is.

294
00:21:39,100 --> 00:21:40,900
And I'm sure you'll
do your best.

295
00:21:42,067 --> 00:21:43,433
But you'll think I'm crazy.

296
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:51,100
I never intended
to follow science

297
00:21:51,100 --> 00:21:53,000
into anything more than a hobby.

298
00:21:54,233 --> 00:21:55,533
But I was curious.

299
00:21:56,867 --> 00:21:58,467
Why things happen
the way they do,

300
00:21:58,467 --> 00:22:00,233
those questions that
no one can answer.

301
00:22:03,167 --> 00:22:04,767
But one day I understood.

302
00:22:06,967 --> 00:22:09,000
It was as if all the
forces in the universe

303
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:14,000
had come together in that
one moment in space and time,

304
00:22:14,067 --> 00:22:15,767
to deliver an answer to me.

305
00:22:17,867 --> 00:22:20,867
All those things we cannot
change but wish we could.

306
00:22:24,767 --> 00:22:27,233
Something reached
out and spoke to me,

307
00:22:28,533 --> 00:22:29,867
and I understood.

308
00:22:32,633 --> 00:22:33,867
To all those that wished

309
00:22:33,867 --> 00:22:35,633
they could see the
beginning of time.

310
00:22:38,133 --> 00:22:40,100
To all those that've
dreamed of witnessing

311
00:22:40,100 --> 00:22:43,633
the first man climb out
of the primordial slime.

312
00:22:45,967 --> 00:22:47,433
Finally they could.

313
00:22:48,733 --> 00:22:51,033
Since H.G. Wells it's been
one of the greatest mysteries

314
00:22:51,033 --> 00:22:54,133
and fantasies in human
history, but not anymore.

315
00:22:56,867 --> 00:22:58,167
I've been given the secret.

316
00:23:01,733 --> 00:23:03,867
And it was so simple.

317
00:23:22,433 --> 00:23:24,000
- I have a hypothetical for you.

318
00:23:25,233 --> 00:23:26,433
- Shoot.

319
00:23:28,700 --> 00:23:30,333
- What if somebody
came to you and said,

320
00:23:30,333 --> 00:23:32,000
"Ovid, I can take you
back to the moment

321
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,433
"your classroom was hit, to
the moment you were injured."

322
00:23:35,600 --> 00:23:36,633
What would you do?

323
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,200
- I'd call the cops.

324
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:41,300
I'm serious.

325
00:23:42,100 --> 00:23:43,000
- What are we
talking about, here?

326
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:43,900
- Will you just humor me?

327
00:23:45,133 --> 00:23:46,267
- I'd think he was crazy.

328
00:23:46,267 --> 00:23:47,667
- But what if were possible?

329
00:23:47,667 --> 00:23:48,600
I mean, wouldn't you
take that opportunity

330
00:23:48,600 --> 00:23:49,867
to set things right?

331
00:23:51,100 --> 00:23:52,167
- "Set things right"?

332
00:23:52,733 --> 00:23:54,467
You mean save my eye?

333
00:23:54,467 --> 00:23:55,767
Avoid the bomb somehow?

334
00:23:55,767 --> 00:23:56,700
- Yeah.

335
00:23:58,533 --> 00:24:00,033
- My life would be different.

336
00:24:01,333 --> 00:24:03,067
You know when you were a
kid, you'd see that crazy guy

337
00:24:03,067 --> 00:24:05,233
walking down the
street with one arm.

338
00:24:05,233 --> 00:24:06,400
You point and you stare,

339
00:24:06,400 --> 00:24:07,667
you whisper to your
friends about him.

340
00:24:08,733 --> 00:24:10,267
Well when you become the
subject of those stares

341
00:24:10,267 --> 00:24:11,867
it really turns the tables.

342
00:24:11,867 --> 00:24:13,900
- So, hypothetically...

343
00:24:15,300 --> 00:24:17,467
- Hypothetically
if I could go back

344
00:24:17,467 --> 00:24:20,067
and save my eye somehow?

345
00:24:20,133 --> 00:24:22,033
Sure, it'd make my life easier.

346
00:24:22,033 --> 00:24:22,900
- Yeah.

347
00:24:23,467 --> 00:24:24,867
- But I wouldn't do it.

348
00:24:25,433 --> 00:24:27,267
I mean, changing what
happened would change my life

349
00:24:27,267 --> 00:24:28,867
and everything
I've done with it.

350
00:24:28,867 --> 00:24:31,567
I mean, teaching
overseas during the wars,

351
00:24:31,567 --> 00:24:33,567
all those kids, who knows
where they would be.

352
00:24:34,433 --> 00:24:35,433
- Okay, you're
right, you're right.

353
00:24:35,433 --> 00:24:36,700
But who knows?

354
00:24:36,700 --> 00:24:37,933
You coulda gone on to
do other great things.

355
00:24:37,933 --> 00:24:39,600
- Let other men do
other great things.

356
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:41,467
I think I'm doing what
I'm supposed to be doing.

357
00:24:41,467 --> 00:24:43,300
- Yeah, but I guess it'd
be impossible to know.

358
00:24:45,233 --> 00:24:47,000
- All right, let
me put it to you.

359
00:24:47,767 --> 00:24:49,767
What if your dad hadn't
died when you were a kid?

360
00:24:52,500 --> 00:24:53,667
- Yeah, I don't know.

361
00:24:54,267 --> 00:24:55,367
- Yeah, but don't you think...

362
00:24:57,200 --> 00:24:59,300
His death defined who you are.

363
00:24:59,300 --> 00:25:00,767
- Yeah, in many ways.

364
00:25:01,200 --> 00:25:02,900
If you could go back
and save his life somehow

365
00:25:02,900 --> 00:25:04,367
do you think you'd be
doing what you're doing?

366
00:25:05,100 --> 00:25:07,533
- Well business as it
is, maybe I shouldn't be.

367
00:25:07,533 --> 00:25:08,933
- Come on, man.

368
00:25:08,933 --> 00:25:12,100
I'm just saying our
lives make us who we are.

369
00:25:12,100 --> 00:25:14,433
And who knows if you'd be
doing what you're doing,

370
00:25:14,433 --> 00:25:16,233
who knows if you'da
got a chance to?

371
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:19,133
- I guess if my dad was
still alive I could've always

372
00:25:19,133 --> 00:25:21,900
become that secret agent
I always wanted to.

373
00:25:22,900 --> 00:25:24,267
- All right, man, you
asked for my opinion,

374
00:25:24,267 --> 00:25:25,633
I'm just giving it to you.

375
00:25:25,633 --> 00:25:27,133
- Oh, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no.

376
00:25:28,467 --> 00:25:29,433
You're right.

377
00:25:30,433 --> 00:25:31,600
Thanks, man.

378
00:25:32,533 --> 00:25:33,867
How's that sandwich?

379
00:25:33,867 --> 00:25:36,033
- Oh, it's awesome.

380
00:25:36,967 --> 00:25:38,300
Your salad good?

381
00:25:38,300 --> 00:25:39,567
- Nah, not really.

382
00:25:41,233 --> 00:25:42,167
- See?

383
00:25:42,167 --> 00:25:43,733
Everything happens for a reason.

384
00:25:47,967 --> 00:25:48,933
So.

385
00:25:50,467 --> 00:25:51,633
Just to clarify.

386
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:55,500
You're telling me
that you're from...

387
00:25:56,267 --> 00:25:57,600
Yes.

388
00:25:59,133 --> 00:26:01,200
And you
discovered some way to...

389
00:26:02,167 --> 00:26:03,500
Yes.

390
00:26:04,233 --> 00:26:05,967
- Well I'd be very
interested in hearing it.

391
00:26:05,967 --> 00:26:07,100
- Oh, I'm sure you would.

392
00:26:08,167 --> 00:26:09,567
My secret's worth a lot.

393
00:26:10,167 --> 00:26:13,100
- Well, we are under doctor
patient confidentiality.

394
00:26:13,500 --> 00:26:14,767
- I know.

395
00:26:14,767 --> 00:26:16,267
- Nothing you can say
can leave these walls.

396
00:26:16,267 --> 00:26:18,667
I encourage my patients
to be as open as possible.

397
00:26:18,667 --> 00:26:21,867
- Assuming that you really
wanna keep your practice.

398
00:26:21,867 --> 00:26:22,767
- Right.

399
00:26:22,767 --> 00:26:23,533
- Do you?

400
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:26,133
- Excuse me?

401
00:26:26,133 --> 00:26:27,700
- Do you wish to
keep your practice?

402
00:26:29,300 --> 00:26:30,667
Do you enjoy what you do?

403
00:26:32,267 --> 00:26:33,200
- Of course.

404
00:26:33,967 --> 00:26:35,267
This is my life.

405
00:26:35,933 --> 00:26:37,633
I try to help people, like you.

406
00:26:38,567 --> 00:26:40,900
- Why do you feel the
need to help other people?

407
00:26:42,433 --> 00:26:45,033
- I believe you walked
into my office today.

408
00:26:45,033 --> 00:26:46,967
- Do you take the
time to help yourself?

409
00:26:46,967 --> 00:26:48,867
- Are you trying to
put me on the couch?

410
00:26:50,067 --> 00:26:51,033
- I'm sorry.

411
00:26:51,900 --> 00:26:52,933
I meant no disrespect.

412
00:26:52,933 --> 00:26:53,700
- No, no, no.

413
00:26:53,700 --> 00:26:54,700
That's fine.

414
00:26:55,700 --> 00:26:57,033
Let's get back to your story.

415
00:26:57,867 --> 00:26:59,100
- Yeah, you're right.

416
00:27:00,333 --> 00:27:04,100
- Can you describe how
the answer came to you?

417
00:27:04,100 --> 00:27:06,500
- How is not as
important as why.

418
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:07,267
- Okay.

419
00:27:08,033 --> 00:27:09,233
What motivated you?

420
00:27:09,733 --> 00:27:11,333
- Surely there are
things in our lives

421
00:27:11,333 --> 00:27:13,100
we wish could be changed.

422
00:27:13,100 --> 00:27:14,533
When you get older, however,

423
00:27:14,533 --> 00:27:16,933
you grow comfortable in
the way things turned out.

424
00:27:18,400 --> 00:27:20,300
That was not the
case for me, Doctor.

425
00:27:20,300 --> 00:27:21,500
- I see.

426
00:27:23,900 --> 00:27:25,400
- Some of the worst
crimes against humanity

427
00:27:25,400 --> 00:27:27,433
are done with the
best of intentions.

428
00:27:27,433 --> 00:27:29,500
This was the greatest
find in history,

429
00:27:29,500 --> 00:27:32,333
and it was bound to
revolutionize the
way people live,

430
00:27:32,333 --> 00:27:33,600
the way they thought.

431
00:27:33,600 --> 00:27:35,267
By sharing it, not only
did I think it would be

432
00:27:35,267 --> 00:27:38,600
a great leap in science, but
would be enhancing the world

433
00:27:38,600 --> 00:27:41,133
with pure,
unadulterated knowledge.

434
00:27:42,367 --> 00:27:44,633
But knowledge is nothing
without understanding.

435
00:27:45,500 --> 00:27:48,267
I made a few calls, the
reaction was immediate.

436
00:27:48,267 --> 00:27:50,167
As you can imagine, it
was much like yours.

437
00:27:50,167 --> 00:27:51,767
A swift nod and a
quick dismissal.

438
00:27:51,767 --> 00:27:53,400
I was nobody.

439
00:27:53,467 --> 00:27:56,567
I was not part of
the well established
scientific community.

440
00:27:56,567 --> 00:27:59,033
I got the government to listen,
they brought me deep inside,

441
00:27:59,033 --> 00:28:01,200
surrounding me with the
world's great scientists.

442
00:28:01,200 --> 00:28:03,133
Not the ones you hear about.

443
00:28:03,133 --> 00:28:07,033
They studied my work,
cross-examined my calculations.

444
00:28:08,767 --> 00:28:10,133
It was real.

445
00:28:10,400 --> 00:28:12,567
Before I even had a
chance to think about it,

446
00:28:12,567 --> 00:28:14,267
the government was at my door

447
00:28:14,267 --> 00:28:16,633
offering me the biggest
check I'd ever seen.

448
00:28:17,433 --> 00:28:19,200
I was young, inexperienced.

449
00:28:20,233 --> 00:28:21,467
The amount of
zeroes on that check

450
00:28:21,467 --> 00:28:23,067
could've fixed a small country.

451
00:28:23,733 --> 00:28:26,467
And they calmly slid it
across the table to me.

452
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:29,267
- So you took the money.

453
00:28:31,067 --> 00:28:32,233
- It was one of those moments

454
00:28:32,233 --> 00:28:34,400
when you're presented
with two roads.

455
00:28:36,433 --> 00:28:39,067
If I'd known the
road that I chose,

456
00:28:39,067 --> 00:28:40,733
would I have made
the same decision?

457
00:28:42,267 --> 00:28:43,933
I would like to think no.

458
00:28:45,700 --> 00:28:47,600
- So what happened after
you took the money?

459
00:28:47,600 --> 00:28:51,000
- I spent some, bought
a new house, car.

460
00:28:52,133 --> 00:28:53,533
Life was great.

461
00:28:53,900 --> 00:28:56,967
I was, I was the most famous
scientist in the world.

462
00:28:56,967 --> 00:28:59,100
And I never considered
myself a scientist.

463
00:28:59,567 --> 00:29:01,100
It was newspapers and magazines,

464
00:29:01,100 --> 00:29:03,500
and talk shows and
movie premieres, and...

465
00:29:04,133 --> 00:29:06,333
Everyone knew my face.

466
00:29:06,333 --> 00:29:08,867
But really quickly, in a
couple years it went public.

467
00:29:08,867 --> 00:29:11,500
You cannot contain
human curiosity.

468
00:29:12,333 --> 00:29:13,733
Everyone's always
looking for the next

469
00:29:13,733 --> 00:29:16,400
great leap in technology,
and this was it.

470
00:29:17,467 --> 00:29:18,600
Got a question?

471
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:21,967
Some time, we'll
give you the answer.

472
00:29:21,967 --> 00:29:23,567
- Yeah, I do have a question.

473
00:29:24,333 --> 00:29:26,033
So how does this thing work?

474
00:29:26,967 --> 00:29:28,567
Anybody can just travel back?

475
00:29:29,500 --> 00:29:31,133
- No, that's not
what I intended.

476
00:29:32,133 --> 00:29:35,467
You can't just give anyone
the power to actually go back.

477
00:29:36,267 --> 00:29:37,933
Think of the
ramifications of that.

478
00:29:39,233 --> 00:29:42,333
What I envisioned was more
like a window in time.

479
00:29:42,333 --> 00:29:43,533
- A window?

480
00:29:43,533 --> 00:29:44,867
Like what, like a,
like a big screen

481
00:29:44,867 --> 00:29:46,500
where you could
just see history?

482
00:29:46,500 --> 00:29:47,967
- Overly simplified, yes.

483
00:29:47,967 --> 00:29:49,733
Once it was released publicly,

484
00:29:49,733 --> 00:29:51,467
people could see any
time they desired

485
00:29:51,467 --> 00:29:54,567
without directly
affecting past events.

486
00:29:54,567 --> 00:29:56,500
It was the only way
to keep it safe.

487
00:29:56,500 --> 00:29:57,867
So we thought.

488
00:29:57,867 --> 00:30:00,267
- So theoretically,
anybody could see anything.

489
00:30:00,267 --> 00:30:02,767
- Think about it
as memory recall.

490
00:30:02,767 --> 00:30:05,300
Every man's experiences, they
can revisit even vividly.

491
00:30:06,100 --> 00:30:09,300
Now imagine events in time
as memories for the world

492
00:30:09,300 --> 00:30:10,833
in a space time continuum.

493
00:30:11,500 --> 00:30:13,167
I discovered a way
to harness that.

494
00:30:13,800 --> 00:30:16,900
- Now you mentioned being able
to see the creation of man.

495
00:30:16,900 --> 00:30:18,567
I mean, you'd have
seen humans assemble,

496
00:30:18,567 --> 00:30:20,500
develop their gods and
destroy each other.

497
00:30:20,500 --> 00:30:21,967
I mean, Jesus Christ.

498
00:30:21,967 --> 00:30:23,433
- He was just a man.

499
00:30:25,533 --> 00:30:28,333
Imagine the devastation
from a revelation like that.

500
00:30:29,700 --> 00:30:31,467
95% of the world's population

501
00:30:31,467 --> 00:30:33,433
believed in a God in some form.

502
00:30:34,700 --> 00:30:38,500
The scientists and
the politicians and
eventually the public

503
00:30:38,500 --> 00:30:39,733
were able to go back and see

504
00:30:39,733 --> 00:30:42,067
the Christian son of
God as a mortal man.

505
00:30:42,067 --> 00:30:43,467
It shook the foundations.

506
00:30:44,200 --> 00:30:47,833
Even atheists began to
lose hope for the future.

507
00:30:48,533 --> 00:30:51,300
Southern evangelists began
lashing out violently

508
00:30:51,300 --> 00:30:53,400
at anybody who supported
the new discovery.

509
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:56,100
The world was more
divided than ever.

510
00:30:56,867 --> 00:31:00,533
The road to hell had been
paved with good intentions.

511
00:31:00,533 --> 00:31:02,133
And it was just the beginning.

512
00:31:03,400 --> 00:31:06,167
- Well what happened,
some kind of big war?

513
00:31:06,167 --> 00:31:08,767
- Once the technology
was simplified,

514
00:31:08,767 --> 00:31:11,567
the government went to a
few large corporations.

515
00:31:11,567 --> 00:31:13,933
To develop it for
high-end consumer use.

516
00:31:14,667 --> 00:31:17,100
They figured it was a great
way to build the world economy.

517
00:31:17,700 --> 00:31:21,000
Like commercial missions
to the moon or Mars.

518
00:31:21,467 --> 00:31:23,267
They figured they could
make a lot of money,

519
00:31:23,267 --> 00:31:24,667
and they were right.

520
00:31:24,667 --> 00:31:26,567
Only the most wealthy
could afford it, at first.

521
00:31:26,567 --> 00:31:30,067
But with any new technology
price decreases with time.

