00:43:41,667 --> 00:43:43,367
I mean, who are we to play God?

784
00:43:43,367 --> 00:43:44,533
What's done is done.

785
00:43:45,333 --> 00:43:46,533
- Yeah, yeah.

786
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:51,633
- Ah, man, you're
really hooked on this.

787
00:43:52,900 --> 00:43:54,033
- What's up?

788
00:43:54,733 --> 00:43:56,300
- You need to take
some time off.

789
00:43:56,300 --> 00:43:58,233
Spend some time with your wife.

790
00:44:00,500 --> 00:44:01,867
How's your marriage, Jason?

791
00:44:02,867 --> 00:44:03,667
- What do you mean, man?

792
00:44:03,667 --> 00:44:04,900
My marriage is fine.

793
00:44:06,433 --> 00:44:07,667
- You sure?

794
00:44:08,367 --> 00:44:10,600
I mean, all you do is
spend time with me,

795
00:44:10,600 --> 00:44:12,367
playing basketball or at work.

796
00:44:12,367 --> 00:44:14,333
- Okay, what happened
to rituals, man?

797
00:44:14,333 --> 00:44:16,667
- Come on, man, I love
you, you're my best friend,

798
00:44:16,667 --> 00:44:19,867
but uh, I mean you have
a pregnant wife at home.

799
00:44:19,867 --> 00:44:21,500
With your first
child, she loves you.

800
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:25,367
And all you do is talk to me
about work, week after week.

801
00:44:26,867 --> 00:44:27,867
- I know.

802
00:44:29,700 --> 00:44:30,867
Are you sure?

803
00:44:31,500 --> 00:44:33,300
- I just gotta
get my head right.

804
00:44:33,300 --> 00:44:34,867
I will.

805
00:44:34,867 --> 00:44:37,100
- I just, I don't want you to
mess things up for yourself.

806
00:44:37,100 --> 00:44:39,533
- How can I mess things
up with you in my corner?

807
00:44:40,900 --> 00:44:42,633
- Okay, but I can't fight
all your battles for you.

808
00:44:42,633 --> 00:44:43,867
- I know, I know.

809
00:44:43,867 --> 00:44:46,033
Especially in your
condition, Jesus.

810
00:44:46,867 --> 00:44:47,533
- Really?

811
00:44:49,400 --> 00:44:50,900
Ass.

812
00:44:51,367 --> 00:44:53,967
- I'm serious, though, I can't
save your marriage for you.

813
00:44:53,967 --> 00:44:54,900
- Does that mean
you're not gonna

814
00:44:54,900 --> 00:44:56,300
write me love sonnets anymore?

815
00:44:57,400 --> 00:44:58,533
- Nope.

816
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:04,333
Okay, maybe for your
birthday, maybe.

817
00:45:09,567 --> 00:45:11,000
- How do you do it, Doctor?

818
00:45:11,867 --> 00:45:12,900
- I'm sorry?

819
00:45:12,900 --> 00:45:14,367
- Manage your relationships?

820
00:45:16,067 --> 00:45:18,867
Surely your wife is lonely
while you're here at work.

821
00:45:18,867 --> 00:45:21,433
Dealing with colorful
characters such as myself.

822
00:45:23,400 --> 00:45:25,333
What does she think of
your chosen profession?

823
00:45:27,300 --> 00:45:29,133
- Our marriage has
its problems, but...

824
00:45:30,967 --> 00:45:32,267
I mean, they always do.

825
00:45:33,700 --> 00:45:35,233
She understands
that this is my job

826
00:45:35,233 --> 00:45:36,700
and this is what supports us.

827
00:45:38,933 --> 00:45:41,100
And every relationship
has its sacrifices.

828
00:45:41,100 --> 00:45:42,533
- What does she
sacrifice for you?

829
00:45:42,533 --> 00:45:44,467
- That's uh, I don't think
that's any of your business.

830
00:45:45,733 --> 00:45:47,233
- How often do you
see your friends?

831
00:45:47,867 --> 00:45:50,067
- Let's backtrack, I don't
wanna get derailed again.

832
00:45:50,867 --> 00:45:52,333
Let's talk about your partner.

833
00:45:53,133 --> 00:45:54,267
Now he was probably
closer to you

834
00:45:54,267 --> 00:45:56,033
than most people around you.

835
00:45:56,900 --> 00:45:58,167
- Yes, he was.

836
00:45:59,867 --> 00:46:01,267
He was one of the
remnants of my life

837
00:46:01,267 --> 00:46:02,867
before everything changed.

838
00:46:04,167 --> 00:46:06,000
Although he was happy for me,

839
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:07,867
he thought that
I should sit back

840
00:46:08,300 --> 00:46:11,333
and enjoy the fruits of
my labor with my family.

841
00:46:12,267 --> 00:46:13,900
But I could not sit still.

842
00:46:15,133 --> 00:46:17,267
I had to be involved
in every adjustment,

843
00:46:17,267 --> 00:46:20,333
every refinement to what
I'd given to the world.

844
00:46:20,333 --> 00:46:22,100
- Don't you mean what
you had sold the world?

845
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:23,867
- Sold.

846
00:46:25,867 --> 00:46:26,900
Yes.

847
00:46:27,267 --> 00:46:28,867
I had to be at
every demonstration.

848
00:46:30,233 --> 00:46:32,100
I might as well have
been government property.

849
00:46:33,100 --> 00:46:36,067
- As your partner stood
by on the sidelines.

850
00:46:36,067 --> 00:46:37,300
- As everyone did.

851
00:46:38,167 --> 00:46:39,667
Everyone that was close to me.

852
00:46:40,700 --> 00:46:42,767
You know, in some ways,

853
00:46:42,767 --> 00:46:44,900
my partner was more
naive than I was.

854
00:46:46,267 --> 00:46:49,100
Once the repercussions
were being felt,

855
00:46:49,100 --> 00:46:52,133
no one could've imagined just
how bad it was gonna get.

856
00:46:53,500 --> 00:46:56,167
He was there to adivse
me, to comfort me even.

857
00:46:56,167 --> 00:46:57,467
To see me through the storm.

858
00:46:57,933 --> 00:47:00,333
Together we tried to
pick up the pieces.

859
00:47:00,333 --> 00:47:02,167
Tried to undo what I had done.

860
00:47:02,900 --> 00:47:04,233
- Did any of it work?

861
00:47:04,233 --> 00:47:05,267
- No.

862
00:47:05,267 --> 00:47:06,633
- Why?

863
00:47:06,633 --> 00:47:09,467
- We tried to stop the
mass consumerization of it.

864
00:47:09,467 --> 00:47:11,133
Plead with the government.

865
00:47:11,133 --> 00:47:13,500
By this time the
damage was too severe.

866
00:47:13,500 --> 00:47:15,700
The technology was
in too many hands.

867
00:47:15,700 --> 00:47:17,867
Unsteady hands at that.

868
00:47:17,867 --> 00:47:19,867
We tried to make attempts
to set things right,

869
00:47:19,867 --> 00:47:21,000
but it was futile.

870
00:47:23,267 --> 00:47:25,100
That's when I decided,
I have to go back.

871
00:47:25,100 --> 00:47:27,633
Some how, some way,
I had to go back.

872
00:47:27,633 --> 00:47:30,167
I fell deeper and
deeper into my work,

873
00:47:30,167 --> 00:47:33,533
trying to push the boundaries
of my initial discovery.

874
00:47:33,533 --> 00:47:35,700
To allow for actual travel.

875
00:47:36,867 --> 00:47:38,867
To send a man into the past.

876
00:47:39,967 --> 00:47:42,067
My partner pleaded
with me to stop.

877
00:47:43,900 --> 00:47:45,100
But I couldn't.

878
00:47:45,867 --> 00:47:47,867
I needed to know if
change was possible.

879
00:47:49,733 --> 00:47:51,667
That's around the
time he turned on me.

880
00:47:52,467 --> 00:47:54,900
- Now when you say
he turned on you,

881
00:47:54,900 --> 00:47:57,100
he didn't merely cut you
out of his life, did he?

882
00:47:57,700 --> 00:47:59,500
- Human beings were
once again reduced

883
00:47:59,500 --> 00:48:03,167
to mindless barbarians
and I was responsible.

884
00:48:03,167 --> 00:48:05,467
We would've been better
off if a meteor had struck

885
00:48:05,467 --> 00:48:06,967
and wiped the slate clean.

886
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:12,400
Or that a bomb had forced
us to start all over again.

887
00:48:14,233 --> 00:48:16,900
But I did it, I
actually did it, Doctor.

888
00:48:16,900 --> 00:48:18,433
See viewing was
only the beginning.

889
00:48:18,433 --> 00:48:20,533
But like a rudimentary
computer it only took time

890
00:48:20,533 --> 00:48:24,333
and development before
a new model was born.

891
00:48:24,333 --> 00:48:26,700
You harness a wormhole,
speed up one end

892
00:48:26,700 --> 00:48:28,200
and slow down the other end.

893
00:48:31,300 --> 00:48:32,567
- Go on, go on.

894
00:48:33,733 --> 00:48:34,767
- I can't.

895
00:48:35,567 --> 00:48:36,567
- Mr. Darnell, you realize--

896
00:48:36,567 --> 00:48:38,600
- Please, please, I can't.

897
00:48:39,067 --> 00:48:39,933
Let's leave it at this.

898
00:48:39,933 --> 00:48:41,200
- How does it work?

899
00:48:43,867 --> 00:48:45,267
How does it work?

900
00:48:45,267 --> 00:48:46,700
- You have to understand
if I answer that question

901
00:48:46,700 --> 00:48:49,167
you could rip a hole through
everything as we know it.

902
00:48:49,167 --> 00:48:51,133
- But that's why
you're here, isn't it?

903
00:48:51,133 --> 00:48:52,367
To change the past,

904
00:48:52,367 --> 00:48:54,033
so you're gonna have
to give me something.

905
00:48:54,033 --> 00:48:55,867
- Doctor Pyatt I was under
the impression it was never

906
00:48:55,867 --> 00:48:58,200
a good idea to force a
patient to divulge anything

907
00:48:58,200 --> 00:48:59,700
they weren't comfortable with.

908
00:48:59,700 --> 00:49:02,067
- I can't, um, I
can't keep doing this.

909
00:49:02,067 --> 00:49:03,333
- All right, all right.

910
00:49:05,133 --> 00:49:06,633
I know this must be frustrating.

911
00:49:11,500 --> 00:49:14,467
I can't give you everything,
it just wouldn't be safe.

912
00:49:19,933 --> 00:49:21,133
- I'm listening.

913
00:49:21,133 --> 00:49:22,400
- You say you like science?

914
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:24,200
- I do.

915
00:49:24,200 --> 00:49:25,367
- Then go back and
read the concepts

916
00:49:25,367 --> 00:49:28,867
presented by Hawking,
Einstein, Lewis.

917
00:49:29,533 --> 00:49:33,633
Light speed, black
holes, wormholes.

918
00:49:35,667 --> 00:49:37,233
They were so close.

919
00:49:37,867 --> 00:49:40,233
There was just one
small piece missing.

920
00:49:41,200 --> 00:49:42,733
I'm sure you're aware,

921
00:49:42,733 --> 00:49:45,300
that you're somewhat familiar
with the concept of wormholes.

922
00:49:45,867 --> 00:49:48,300
- Sure, yeah, they're
fascinating to wonder about.

923
00:49:48,933 --> 00:49:51,000
- If you don't mind, could
you tell me what you know?

924
00:49:53,667 --> 00:49:54,867
- Um...

925
00:49:56,667 --> 00:49:58,300
They're a consequence
of Einstein's

926
00:49:58,300 --> 00:50:00,133
theory of general relativity.

927
00:50:00,633 --> 00:50:02,433
A wormhole in theory would,

928
00:50:03,933 --> 00:50:07,733
act as a shortcut or a passage
way through space and time.

929
00:50:08,700 --> 00:50:11,367
- The physics are even
simpler than your definition.

930
00:50:11,367 --> 00:50:12,867
A wormhole creates a tunnel

931
00:50:12,867 --> 00:50:15,700
effectively cutting through
two locations in space time.

932
00:50:15,700 --> 00:50:17,500
- Yeah, yeah, therefore
eliminating the need

933
00:50:17,500 --> 00:50:19,700
for three dimensional
travel through space.

934
00:50:19,700 --> 00:50:21,200
No more rocket ships.

935
00:50:21,200 --> 00:50:22,833
I like Stargate, too.

936
00:50:22,833 --> 00:50:24,500
- Oh, wow, Stargate.

937
00:50:25,500 --> 00:50:27,567
It's been a long time
since I've seen that movie.

938
00:50:28,367 --> 00:50:29,533
Who was that guy in it,

939
00:50:29,533 --> 00:50:31,167
he was really good
in that old western?

940
00:50:33,167 --> 00:50:34,367
- What, Kurt Russell?

941
00:50:34,367 --> 00:50:35,867
- Kurt Russell, he
was good, wasn't he?

942
00:50:35,867 --> 00:50:39,233
- Listen, nothing you are
telling me is new information,

943
00:50:39,233 --> 00:50:41,767
all right, the theories
about wormholes have existed

944
00:50:41,767 --> 00:50:45,800
for a long time, but nobody
knows if they actually exist

945
00:50:45,800 --> 00:50:47,600
or how to find them.

946
00:50:47,600 --> 00:50:48,500
- But I do.

947
00:50:49,267 --> 00:50:50,533
They're everywhere.

948
00:50:50,867 --> 00:50:52,800
Just a matter of seeing
them or harnessing them.

949
00:50:52,800 --> 00:50:55,333
- But you haven't
explained either.

950
00:50:56,633 --> 00:50:57,867
How do you see them?

951
00:50:59,233 --> 00:51:00,367
How do you harness them?

952
00:51:00,900 --> 00:51:02,400
A machine, some sort of gateway?

953
00:51:02,400 --> 00:51:04,967
- Of course you need a
machine to sustain a wormhole.

954
00:51:05,867 --> 00:51:07,167
But this is where I stop.

955
00:51:08,100 --> 00:51:09,667
I have given you the gun.

956
00:51:10,533 --> 00:51:11,900
Let me keep the bullets.

957
00:51:19,033 --> 00:51:20,167
- Please, continue.

958
00:51:22,867 --> 00:51:24,433
- I found a way to go back.

959
00:51:24,433 --> 00:51:26,567
I was alone, but I found it.

960
00:51:27,333 --> 00:51:29,133
My old partner was the
only one that knew,

961
00:51:29,133 --> 00:51:31,100
but for now, it'll
stay that way.

962
00:51:32,367 --> 00:51:34,667
The only question is,
can the ripples I create

963
00:51:34,667 --> 00:51:37,367
be enough to change the future?

964
00:51:37,367 --> 00:51:39,767
Or create an alternate one?

965
00:51:39,767 --> 00:51:41,000
- Ripples?

966
00:51:43,300 --> 00:51:45,533
- Think of the water
in that glass as time.

967
00:51:46,233 --> 00:51:48,467
Time moves forward
constantly, untouched,

968
00:51:48,467 --> 00:51:49,667
as still as the water.

969
00:51:50,267 --> 00:51:52,000
Go back and try to
change something,

970
00:51:53,867 --> 00:51:55,433
and it creates a ripple effect.

971
00:51:56,500 --> 00:51:58,067
Change has to
catch up with time.

972
00:52:02,300 --> 00:52:05,667
And everything around it
either changes, or suffers.

973
00:52:08,100 --> 00:52:10,600
- Unless the ripples were
always meant to happen.

974
00:52:10,600 --> 00:52:11,933
- That's what I wanna find out.

975
00:52:16,233 --> 00:52:17,633
The truth is, he
had every reason

976
00:52:17,633 --> 00:52:19,400
and every right to want me dead.

977
00:52:20,267 --> 00:52:21,600
I would've done it
myself if I'd thought

978
00:52:21,600 --> 00:52:22,867
that would change anything.

979
00:52:23,667 --> 00:52:26,033
- Would you say you have
suicidal tendencies?

980
00:52:27,767 --> 00:52:29,367
- I feel that ultimately
I will have to

981
00:52:29,367 --> 00:52:31,633
pay for my sins with my life.

982
00:52:32,867 --> 00:52:35,633
I now am only here to set
the wrong things right.

983
00:52:38,167 --> 00:52:39,967
My parter pursued
me at great length

984
00:52:39,967 --> 00:52:41,600
once he knew what I had done.

985
00:52:43,100 --> 00:52:45,300
And as much as I felt
it was on my shoulders

986
00:52:45,300 --> 00:52:48,667
to set everything
right, he was convinced

987
00:52:48,667 --> 00:52:50,700
that anything I did
to fix the present

988
00:52:51,867 --> 00:52:53,933
would continue to
make matters worse.

989
00:52:54,567 --> 00:52:57,000
- Have you ever thought
that he may be right?

990
00:52:57,000 --> 00:52:58,300
- He might be.

991
00:52:58,300 --> 00:52:59,333
I don't know yet.

992
00:53:00,867 --> 00:53:02,100
I think it's worth the risk.

993
00:53:04,267 --> 00:53:06,733
I'm just afraid of what
lengths he might go to,

994
00:53:07,967 --> 00:53:09,567
to see his mission through.

995
00:53:11,033 --> 00:53:12,233
- And your wife?

996
00:53:13,233 --> 00:53:14,567
Did you lose her, too?

997
00:53:16,500 --> 00:53:17,900
- You know that saying,

998
00:53:17,900 --> 00:53:19,700
you don't know what you've
got until you lost it?

999
00:53:20,333 --> 00:53:21,533
- Sure.

1000
00:53:22,267 --> 00:53:24,967
- When I was a young
man, she kept me steady.

1001
00:53:26,267 --> 00:53:28,000
I cannot remember
the precise moment

1002
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:29,500
where it all fell apart.

1003
00:53:29,500 --> 00:53:30,433
It was gradual.

1004
00:53:32,133 --> 00:53:34,033
Like a small scale of illusion.

1005
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:37,700
Just somewhere down the line,

1006
00:53:38,667 --> 00:53:40,967
she realized I couldn't
give her what she needed.

1007
00:53:42,400 --> 00:53:43,767
I didn't even put up a fight.

1008
00:53:44,933 --> 00:53:48,367
I apologized, watched
her walk away.

1009
00:53:49,267 --> 00:53:50,700
- Did you love her?

1010
00:53:50,700 --> 00:53:51,867
- Yes, I did.

1011
00:53:51,867 --> 00:53:53,233
- And you just let her go?

1012
00:53:54,767 --> 00:53:56,733
- I might not have loved
her if she'd stayed.

1013
00:53:57,867 --> 00:53:59,967
How can I respect
someone who stayed

1014
00:53:59,967 --> 00:54:02,233
with someone that couldn't
even respect themselves?

1015
00:54:02,867 --> 00:54:04,500
- Well I think if
you love somebody,

1016
00:54:06,100 --> 00:54:07,500
you make it work
through anything.

1017
00:54:09,067 --> 00:54:10,367
I think it's that simple.

1018
00:54:12,467 --> 00:54:13,867
Have you ever considered
you couldn't handle

1019
00:54:13,867 --> 00:54:15,967
being there for her
because you didn't want it?

1020
00:54:15,967 --> 00:54:17,433
Or you were afraid of it?

1021
00:54:17,867 --> 00:54:20,167
- Doctor Pyatt, if you weren't
sitting here talking to me

1022
00:54:20,167 --> 00:54:21,867
right now, what
would you be doing?

1023
00:54:23,133 --> 00:54:26,167
- I'd be sitting here waiting
for somebody else to talk to.

1024
00:54:26,167 --> 00:54:28,000
- You wouldn't be
home with your wife?

1025
00:54:29,433 --> 00:54:30,567
- This is my job.

1026
00:54:31,567 --> 00:54:32,767
It's what makes us money.

1027
00:54:32,767 --> 00:54:34,533
- You're a psychologist
without patients.

1028
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:37,767
That would explain that
ridiculous brochure.

1029
00:54:38,167 --> 00:54:39,767
No, you wouldn't be
sitting here doing nothing,

1030
00:54:39,767 --> 00:54:41,867
because Doctor,
